  "title": "Compound Events",
  "subtitle": "Two-step experiments and independent events",
  "topics": ["Two-step experiments", "Independent events"],
  "intro": [
    "Compound events combine more than one action, like flipping two coins or rolling two dice. To find their probabilities, first list the full sample space: with two coins there are 2 \u00d7 2 = 4 outcomes, and with two dice there are 6 \u00d7 6 = 36 ordered outcomes.",
    "These actions are independent \u2014 the first result doesn't change the second \u2014 so you can multiply individual probabilities. You'll count favorable outcomes for events like \"exactly one head,\" \"at least one head,\" or a particular dice sum, and see why some sums (like 7) are far more likely than others."
  ],
